  "prompt": "What is the meaning of f(2) in calculus?",
  "response": "In calculus, \\( f(2) \\) represents the value of the function \\( f \\) evaluated at the point \\( x = 2 \\). This means you substitute \\( x = 2 \\) into the function \\( f(x) \\) and compute the corresponding output.\n\n### Example:\nIf \\( f(x) = 3x^2 + 2x - 1 \\), then to find \\( f(2) \\), substitute \\( x = 2 \\):\n\n\\[\nf(2) = 3(2)^2 + 2(2) - 1\n\\]\n\\[\nf(2) = 3(4) + 4 - 1\n\\]\n\\[\nf(2) = 12 + 4 - 1\n\\]\n\\[\nf(2) = 15\n\\]\n\nThus, \\( f(2) = 15 \\).\n\nIn calculus, \\( f(2) \\) is often used to:\n1. Evaluate the function at a specific point.\n2. Determine the \\( y \\)-value corresponding to \\( x = 2 \\) on the graph of \\( f(x) \\).\n3. Use it in further calculations, such as finding the derivative or integral at that point.\n\nLet me know if you'd like further clarification!",
